        "bullets": [
            "IRGC struck US carrier logistics and fueling platforms at Port of Duqm, Oman, in what Iranian state media calls a third-phase retaliatory operation.",
            "Iran's IRGC declared the Strait of Hormuz closed until further notice, per Mehr News; the US reports vessels still transiting and contests the closure.",
            "Crisis Pressure holds at 86 (extreme) while the 30-day Escalation Forecast sits at 61 (high), with Polymarket closure odds as the top forecast driver."
        ],
        "date": "2026-07-12",
        "generatedAt": "2026-07-12T11:52:21.139Z",
        "source": "claude",
        "summary": "The Strait of Hormuz is the site of sharply conflicting operational claims this morning. Iranian state media (IRNA, Mehr News) report that the IRGC has formally declared the strait closed until US military operations cease, struck a second vessel it says violated navigation regulations, and conducted strikes on US logistics infrastructure at Port of Duqm in Oman and Prince Hassan airbase in Jordan. US and CENTCOM reporting, however, describes vessels continuing to transit and sees no evidence of a physical closure; the site's posture treats the closure as real for carrier movements while the broader transit picture remains contested. PortWatch's most recently published figure, recorded on 2026-07-05, shows 34 transits through the strait on that date, against a pre-crisis baseline of 88 per day. Separately, an independent scraper of Gulf-port arrivals logged 565 vessel arrivals in the most recent 24 hours, though that figure uses a different methodology and geographic scope and cannot be compared directly to the PortWatch count. Brent is quoted at $76.01, unchanged since the 2026-07-11 brief; the feed has not produced a new print. The Hormuz Index Crisis Pressure reading of 86 (extreme) reflects immediate event pressure, while the 30-day Escalation Forecast of 61 (high) diverges modestly, driven primarily by Polymarket closure odds, suggesting markets price some probability of de-escalation over the medium term even as the present-state reading remains at its ceiling band.",
        "transitsToday": 34
    },
